## Top-level field values

| attribute | constraints |
|---|---|
| `name` | Required. 1-128 characters. |
| `enabled` | Optional. Boolean. Defaults to `true`. |
| `type` | Required. One of the values below. **Immutable** â€” changing it forces replacement (the `config` shape is type-coupled). |
| `streams` | Required. Set of stream values below; **at least one**. |
| `min_severity` | Optional. One of the severity values below. Defaults to `info`. |
| `config` | Required, sensitive. Per-type JSON blob set with `jsonencode(...)`; see the per-type tables below. |

### `type` values

| type | config shape |
|---|---|
| `syslog` | Syslog config (see below). No secret fields. |
| `webhook` | Webhook config (see below). Auth may carry secret fields. |

### `streams` values

At least one is required. The set is order-independent.

| stream | meaning |
|---|---|
| `security` | Security audit log events |
| `policy` | Session policy log events |
| `api` | API access log events |
| `app` | Application / worker log events |

### `min_severity` values

Only events at or above this severity are forwarded. Defaults to `info`.

| min_severity | meaning |
|---|---|
| `info` | informational and above (lowest threshold; the default) |
| `low` | low and above |
| `medium` | medium and above |
| `high` | high and above |
| `critical` | critical only (highest threshold) |

## The `config` JSON blob

`config` is an opaque, per-`type` JSON object written with `jsonencode(...)`. Its
shape is determined by `type` and must include a matching `type` discriminator
field inside the blob. The fields below are the complete set the backend accepts;
any other key is rejected.

**Secret handling.** Webhook `auth` secret fields (marked below) are encrypted at
rest and **masked to `****`** in every API response. As with `credential_data`,
the provider stores `config` **from your configuration** and does **not** read it
back from the server. Two consequences:

- After **importing** a webhook destination, its secret is unknown until you
  re-supply the full `config` in HCL â€” a webhook secret cannot be recovered from
  the masked server value.
- For webhook destinations, out-of-band changes to the **non-secret** parts of
  `config` (url, method, headers, etc.) are **not** detected as drift, because the
  whole `config` is preserved from state. This is the documented trade-off of the
  stored-from-config rule (identical to `credential_data`).
- `config` is **excluded from import** (only `id` is set on import); re-supply it
  in HCL, exactly like `credential_data`.

### `type = "syslog"` config

Syslog has **no secret fields**.

| field | type | required | default | secret |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `type` | string const `"syslog"` | yes (discriminator) | â€” | no |
| `host` | string | **yes** | â€” | no |
| `port` | integer (1-65535) | **yes** | â€” | no |
| `protocol` | string enum | **yes** | â€” | no |
| `format` | string enum | **yes** | â€” | no |
| `facility` | string enum | no | `local0` | no |
| `tls_verify` | boolean | no | `true` | no |

`protocol` values:

| protocol |
|---|
| `UDP` |
| `TCP` |
| `TLS` |

`format` values:

| format |
|---|
| `RFC3164` |
| `RFC5424` |
| `CEF` |

`facility` values: `local0`, `local1`, `local2`, `local3`, `local4`, `local5`,
`local6`, `local7` (default `local0`).

Example:

```hcl
config = jsonencode({
  type       = "syslog"
  host       = "logs.example.com"
  port       = 6514
  protocol   = "TLS"     # UDP | TCP | TLS
  format     = "RFC5424" # RFC3164 | RFC5424 | CEF
  facility   = "local1"  # local0..local7 (default local0)
  tls_verify = true
})
```

### `type = "webhook"` config

| field | type | required | default | secret |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `type` | string const `"webhook"` | yes (discriminator) | â€” | no |
| `url` | string | **yes** | â€” | no |
| `method` | string enum | no | `POST` | no |
| `headers` | object (stringâ†’string map) | no | `{}` | no |
| `auth` | object (see auth variants) | no | `{ "type": "none" }` | contains secrets |
| `body_format` | string enum | no | `raw` | no |
| `timeout_seconds` | integer (1-60) | no | `5` | no |
| `tls_verify` | boolean | no | `true` | no |

`method` values:

| method |
|---|
| `POST` |
| `PUT` |

`body_format` values:

| body_format | meaning |
|---|---|
| `raw` | raw JSON event body |
| `splunk_hec` | Splunk HTTP Event Collector envelope |

#### Webhook `auth` variants

`auth` is itself a discriminated object keyed by `auth.type`. Choose one of the
four types below. The **secret** fields are masked to `****` by the API and stored
from config (see the secret-handling note above).

| auth.type | fields | secret field(s) |
|---|---|---|
| `none` | `type` only | _(none)_ |
| `bearer` | `type`, `token` (minLength 1) | **`token`** |
| `basic` | `type`, `username` (1-255), `password` (minLength 1) | **`password`** |
| `header` | `type`, `header_name` (1-255), `header_value` (minLength 1) | **`header_value`** |

Example (bearer auth):

```hcl
config = jsonencode({
  type            = "webhook"
  url             = "https://siem.example.com/ingest"
  method          = "POST" # POST | PUT
  body_format     = "raw"  # raw | splunk_hec
  timeout_seconds = 5      # 1..60
  tls_verify      = true
  headers = {
    "X-Source" = "mistershell"
  }
  auth = {
    type  = "bearer"
    token = var.webhook_token # secret; masked by the API, stored from config
  }
})
```

Example (basic auth):

```hcl
config = jsonencode({
  type = "webhook"
  url  = "https://siem.example.com/ingest"
  auth = {
    type     = "basic"
    username = "svc-logs"
    password = var.webhook_password # secret
  }
})
```

